{[%evp 9,100,61,83,32,30,28,34,30,38,-16,46,42,45,26,19,24,27,9,15,-49,63,-42,15,0,0,-54,-46,-55,-63,-330,-327,-392,-392,-394,-362,-412,-436,-439,-429,-421,-414,-424,-450,-456,-216,-459,-443,-441,-408,-548,-542,-568,-531,-741,-758,-738,-651,-674,-646,-742,-620,-658,-646,-643,-625,-722,-730,-622,-620,-687,-814,-833,-803,-832,-841,-845,-790,-895,-807,-1172,-960,-1338,-1014,-742,-817,-985,-985,-1594,-1082,-29992,-29991,-29990,-29988] B06: Modern Defence Current Reputation: Playable for both sides With the Danzhou super tournament being the only truly prestigious event that was under way last week, I basically had somewhat limited options for this survey. Naiditsch's convincing win against Bu Xiangzhi was thus a safe pick, as it exemplified a dream scenario for players of White: obstruction of Black's development, early weakening of his pawn structure that couldn't have been prevented due to poor piece coordination. Such an outcome naturally calls for some scrutiny, and I'm going to present my findings in this article.} 1. e4 g6 2. d4 Bg7 3. Nc3 a6 4. f4 d6 5. Nf3 Nd7 (5... b5 6. Bd3 Bb7 7. a4 b4 8. Ne2 Nd7 9. c3 c5 10. O-O Nh6 11. Ng3 cxd4 12. cxd4 Qb6 13. Bc2 a5 14. h3 d5 15. e5 e6 16. Be3 Ba6 17. Rf2 O-O-O 18. Bd3 Kb7 19. Bxa6+ Qxa6 20. Rc1 {½-½ Feher,G (2583)-Lubbers,J (2419) 12/(156) Cande 2011 (11)}) 6. Bd3 {[%eval 32,18]} (6. a4 $16 {[%eval 83,19]}) (6. Bc4 e6 7. a4 Ne7 8. O-O d5 9. Bd3 dxe4 10. Nxe4 b6 11. Qe2 Bb7 12. c3 O-O 13. a5 c5 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. Be3 Qc7 16. Nfd2 Nd5 17. Nc4 Nxe3 18. Qxe3 Bd5 19. Rf2 Rfd8 20. Re1 Rab8 {0-1 9.b3 a5 10.a4 e6 11.f4 (2201)-Juarez B,S (2513) WLS/Cong Inv 2016 (2)}) 6... c5 $14 7. Be3 $146 (7. d5 b5 8. O-O Bb7 9. a4 c4 10. Be2 b4 11. Na2 Rc8 12. Be3 a5 13. c3 b3 14. Nc1 Ngf6 15. Bd4 O-O 16. Nd2 Nb6 17. Bf3 Nfd7 18. Ne2 Nc5 19. Bxc5 Rxc5 20. Nd4 Qd7 21. Ra3 Rcc8 {Black Or White Limo,S-Sicilian Defense: Rossolimo V,6 426 Linz 2015} 22. Bg4 Bxd4+ 23. cxd4 f5 24. Bh3 Rc7 25. exf5 gxf5 26. Qh5 Bxd5 27. Nf3 e6 28. Ng5 Qg7 29. Qd1 h6