{[%evp 21,68,52,59,21,16,3,18,-144,-131,-124,-70,-102,-102,-129,-126,-124,-84,-229,-226,-276,-247,-271,-265,-247,-207,-268,-273,-339,-330,-376,-366,-364,-364,-364,-188,-376,-202,-190,-139,-361,-327,-459,-384,-458,-396,-1122,-1174,-1120,-1378] B67: Sicilian: Richter-Rauzer: 7...a6 8 0-0-0 Bd7, lines without 9 f4 Be7 Upon winning the Candidates Tournament in October of 1955, Olga was supposed to face the defending champion, Elisaveta Bykova. Instead, FIDE organized a triangular competition between the top 3 players of the world at that time. So, in addition to Olga and Bykova, former world champion Lyudmila Rudenko entered the arena. Their unusual tournament was held in Moscow in 1956 and involved 8-game mini-matches. These three ladies had several Moscow championships and Soviet championships under their belts. Just a few years earlier, Rudenko had bested both crowning herself world champion. Back then, Olga had been runner-up. Bykova, the youngest of the trio, had defeated Rudenko in a match and then successfully defended her title against a brilliant challenger, Kira Zvorykina. So Olga was likely the underdog, the only one of the three who had not clenched the world title. Olga eventually prevailed by scoring half a point more than Bykova in the overall table. The following game has our chapter's protagonist clashing with Rudenko, who was featured in the 3rd chapter of this course--see Lyudmila, the Second. [/course/102010/4]} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8. O-O-O Bd7 9. f4 (9. f3 h6 10. Be3 h5 11. Bg5 Rc8 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. Qe1 Qc7 14. Bd3 b5 15. Kb1 Be7 16. Qh4 b4 17. Ne2 a5 18. Nd4 Bd7 19. f4 a4 20. Ba6 Rb8 21. e5 dxe5 22. fxe5 Qxe5 23. Bf4 Qa5 {Hevia Alejano,C (2476)-Borges Matos,J (2472) La Habana (open) 113/65 2011}) 9... b5 $146 (9... h6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Kb1 (11. f5 Qc7 12. g3 h5 13. Kb1 O-O-O 14. Bh3 Nxd4 15. Qxd4 Be7 16. Rd3 Kb8 17. Ne2 Rc8 18. Rc3 Qa5 19. Rxc8+ Rxc8 20. Nc3 Qe5 21. Qxe5 dxe5 22. Rd1 Kc7 23. Bg2 Bb4 24. fxe6 fxe6 25. Rd3 Bc6 {0-1 Petrovic,S (1871)-9.d1 b7 10.e4_70102 (2400) 42/131 Baku 1986 (6)}) 11... Qb6 12. Nb3 O-O-O 13. Be2 h5 14. Rhf1 Be7 15. Na4 Qa7 16. Bf3 h4 17. Nc3 Kb8 18. Nd5 exd5 19. exd5 Ne5 20. fxe5 fxe5 21. Be4 Rdf8 22. Bf5 Bb5 23. Rf3 Rhg8 24. Re1 {½-½ Mondry,M (2302)-Mateuta,G (2430) 5/17 Sofia 1968} Ba4 25. a3 Qb6 26. Qe2 Bg5 27. Qe4 Qb5 28. Nc1 Qa5 29. Nd3 Be8 30. Ref1 Qc7 31. c4 Rg7 32. Rh3 Rfg8 33. g3 hxg3 34. hxg3 Bd8 35. c5 Bb5 36. Rc1 Rxg3 37. Rxg3 Rxg3 38. cxd6 Bxd3+ 39. Qxd3 {½-½ Mauro,L (2302)-Bulla,J (2430) EU-ch65 sf11 email 2003}) (9... Be7 10. Nf3 Qa5 11. e5 Nd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd2+ 13. Rxd2 exd5 14. Bxe7 Kxe7 15. Rxd5 dxe5 16. Nxe5 Rhd8 17. Rxd7+ Rxd7 18. Nxd7 Kxd7 19. Bc4 f5 20. Re1 Re8 21. Rxe8 Kxe8 22. Bd5 Nd4 23. Kd2 b6 24. a4 {1-0 5) Olga The Fourth-Rubtsova,O Queens of the Chess Board 2023}) 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. f5 {[%eval 21,19]} (12. Qe1 $14 {[%eval 59,22] was preferrable.}) 12... b4 $11 {aiming for ...Qa5.} 13. Ne2 {fxe6 would now be deadly.} e5 14. Ng3 $2 {[%eval -144,21]} (14. Kb1 $1 $11 {[%eval 18,19]}) 14... h5 $1 $17 {And now ...Bh6 would win.} 15. Qe2 ({Much weaker is} 15. Qxb4 h4 16. Ne2 d5 $17) 15... Bb5 {[%eval -70,23]} ({Black should try} 15... h4 $17 {[%eval -124,22]} 16. Nh5 Ke7) 16. Qf3 h4 $36 {[%mdl 2048] White is under strong pressure.} 17. Nh5 {[#]} Ke7 $1 18. Kb1 Bh6 {[%eval -84,21]} (18... Qc7 $142 {[%eval -124,22]}) 19. Qg4 {[%eval -229,21] [#]} (19. g3 $17 {[%eval -84,21]}) 19... Qc7 $1 $19 20. Bd3 Rac8 {...Bxd3 is the strong threat.} 21. Qe2 Bg5 {[%cal Oh8h5] White is weak on the dark squares} 22. g4 Rb8 23. h3 Rhc8 24. Rh2 (24. Bxb5 Rxb5 25. Rh2 Qc6) 24... Qc6 25. Rf2 a5 26. Rf3 a4 {[%cal Ob4b3]} 27. Bxb5 Qxb5 {[%eval -188,17]} (27... Rxb5 $142 {[%eval -364,23]} 28. Rfd3 Rd8) 28. Qf2 $2 {[%eval -376,19]} (28. Qxb5 {[%eval -188,17]} Rxb5 29. b3) 28... Qc5 {[%eval -202,20]} (28... Rc6 $142 {[%eval -376,19] White must now prevent ...Rbc8.} 29. Qf1 Qxf1 30. Rfxf1 Rbc8) 29. Qxc5 Rxc5 30. a3 $2 